{"cursor":"2804","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":", from a manuscript in the BibliothÃ¨que Nationale ]]\n\n'Gaucelm Faidit' ( literally \"Gaucelm the Dispossessed\" c. 1170 – c.\n1202) was a troubadour, born in Uzerche, in the Limousin, from a family of\nknights in service of the count of Turenne. He travelled widely in France,\nSpain, and Hungary. His known patrons include Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany and\nDalfi d'Alvernha; he was at one time in Poitiers at the court of Richard I of\nEngland, for whose death he wrote a famous [[planh]] (lament). It is possible,\nbut controversial, that Gaucelm took part in the Third Crusade from 1189â1191;\nit seems clear that in 1202 he set out on the Fourth Crusade, as did his\ncurrent patron, Boniface of Montferrat. After 1202 there is no further\nhistorical trace of him.\n\nThree sources - the anonymous [[Vida (Occitan literary form)|vida]] (biography)\nof Gaucelm, an exchange of verses between Gaucelm and Elias d'Ussel, and the\nsatirical [[sirventes]] on rival troubadours by the Monk of Montaudon - allege\nthat Gaucelm married a prostitute. According to the vida, her name was Guillelma\nMonja: \"she was very beautiful and well educated\" and accompanied her husband on\nCrusade. The vida also claims that Gaucelm was rather fat, and that after their\nmarriage, Guillelma also put on weight.\n\nAbout seventy of Gaucelm's poems and fourteen of his melodies survive. Six poems\nare addressed to Boniface of Montferrat, and twelve to Maria de Ventadorn.\nSeveral of his poems are accompanied in the manuscripts by detailed explanations\n([[RazÃ³ (Occitan literary form)|razÃ³s]]), usually concerning love affairs and\nrivalries that allegedly inspired the poems. These tales involve Gaucelm with\nHugh IX of Lusignan, his son Hugh X, Alfonso II, Count of Provence, and others.\n","linknr":123,"url":"Gaucelm_Faidit","recorded":1375077344,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Gaucelm_Faidit&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Gaucelm_